  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Where can I get a custom one-off plastic part manufactured?",
  "response": "To get a custom one-off plastic part manufactured, you have several options to consider:\n\n1. **3D Printing Services**: \n   - **Online Platforms**: Websites like Shapeways, Sculpteo, and i.materialise offer 3D printing services where you can upload your design and choose your material. They handle the printing and shipping.\n   - **Local 3D Printing Shops**: Many cities have local 3D printing shops or makerspaces that offer custom printing services. You can search for these in your area and contact them directly.\n\n2. **CNC Machining Services**:\n   - CNC machining can be used for producing plastic parts. Companies like Protolabs and Xometry offer online services where you can upload your design and receive a quote.\n\n3. **Injection Molding Services**:\n   - For a single part, injection molding might be cost-prohibitive due to tooling costs, but some companies offer low-volume injection molding or rapid tooling. Companies like Protolabs might offer such services.\n\n4. **Makerspaces/Fab Labs**:\n   - Many makerspaces and Fab Labs are equipped with plastic manufacturing equipment and can assist with creating your custom part. They often have community members or staff who can help with design and production.\n\n5. **Local Machine Shops**:\n   - Some traditional machine shops have adapted to include plastic machining or have relationships with plastic manufacturers. It might be worthwhile reaching out to local shops to see if they offer such services.\n\n6. **Online Marketplaces**:\n   - Websites like Etsy, MakeXYZ, or even posting a job on service marketplaces like Upwork or Fiverr can connect you with individual manufacturers or small businesses specializing in custom fabrication.\n\n7. **Custom Manufacturing Companies**:\n   - Companies like Fictiv offer custom manufacturing services and can handle both design and production for bespoke plastic parts.\n\nEnsure you have a detailed design, preferably a 3D model, ready to share with the manufacturer for an accurate quote. Be sure to discuss the specifics of your project, including the material preferences, tolerances, and any other requirements you may have.",
